Everything is so magical when your a child. A few days ago while on a hike with family, I caught myself picking up a fossil. I do this often if I see an arrowhead, fossil , petrified wood, or just any rock that I find interesting. The kids with me started looking for rocks as well showing me and asking questions. I explained what types of rocks they had found and how igneous, sedimentary, and metamorphic rocks are formed then helped them identify different types. A friend who was with me made the comment that they have seldom seen me exhibit the amount of enthusiasm, contentment and happiness as when I am rock hunting .I thought back and it struck me how often I pick up rocks. I laughed as I remembered my girlfriend Cara and I walking down the beach in high school and how unbeknownst to her I kept dropping shells in her backpack. She would complain every so often that she felt like her bag kept getting heavier and heavier. I laughed and after our two mile walk home, when she opened her bag she just laughed and said she should have guessed it was my rock obsession not her getting tired that was weighing her down. Such good memories.

? Palácio de La Moneda ??. Como falar de qualquer passeio no Chile sem falar de sua capital? Santiago sempre merece nem que sejam 2 dias de sua viagem (normalmente você já é obrigado a fazer escala lá mesmo, por que não ficar?). A capital tem um centro cheio de histórias, muitas tristes, como é o caso da sua sede do governo. Durante o golpe de Estado em 1973, que instalou a ditadura militar no Chile, o prédio foi duramente bombardeado e o então presidente do país, Salvador Allende, foi morto ali durante os ataques. Além do palácio e de seus arredores, não deixe de visitar o Cerro San Cristóbal, pequena montanha no meio da cidade que dá uma bela visão do centro urbano de Santiago (ps.: verifique as condições climáticas antes de ir, dependendo pode ser que você não veja nada além de nuvens).
Close ur eyes, take a deep breath and enjoooy...?
